# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: accredited-crane-operator-certification
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] According to the new OSHA regulation, employers are now responsible for ensuring the qualification and certification of any operators on their job site.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] It states, "The employer must ensure that ... the operator is qualified or certified to operate the equipment." Employers are also responsible to provide the certification at no cost to the operators.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] This new emphasis on qualification and certification has created a large need in the industry to be filled by various certifying companies.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] Organizations that offer certification must meet a number of guidelines established by OSHA.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] NCCA was the first certifying agency to grant accreditation for crane and rigging personnel.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] It is the oldest provider of certification tests in the USA.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] ANSI is the other nationally recognized accrediting organization; ANSI also internationally accredits personnel certification programs to ISO 17024 (General Requirements for Bodies Operating Certification Systems of Persons).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] ANSI provides 45 personnel accreditation's across multiple industries.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] A number of organizations have been recognized by OSHA for offering certification in the crane and lifting industry.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] These organizations include the not-for-profit organizations National Center for Construction Education and Research (NCCER), the National Commission for the Certification of Crane Operators (NCCCO), and the Operating Engineers Certification Program (OECP).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] Operators attempting to gain certification must pass both a written and practical examination.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] These tests must also be routinely audited for the certifying agencies to maintain their accreditation.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] OSHA regulation 1926.1427(j) describes the standards both the written and practical tests must meet.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/accredited-crane-operator-certification] However, these tests will greatly vary depending on which organization administers them.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/american-national-standards-institute] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] Founded in 1896, it currently represents roughly 400,000 workers in approximately 123 local unions and operates nearly 100 apprenticeship programs.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] In the late 1800s, working conditions were harsh for construction and stationary workers.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] Low wages, no benefits and 60–90 hour workweeks were the norm.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] In 1896, 11 individuals met in Chicago and formed the **National Union of Steam Engineers of America**, the forerunner to the IUOE.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] One year later, the organization began to admit Canadian members and changed its name to the **International Union of Steam Engineers**.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] By 1912, the organization changed its name again to the **International Union of Steam and Operating Engineers**.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] In 1927, the union absorbed the International Brotherhood of Steam Shovel and Dredgemen.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] The union dropped the word "steam" in 1928 as both the technology and the scope of labor had moved beyond steam technology.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] During the era of the two world wars and beyond, IUOE members were a significant part of the defense effort, from the Navy Seabees, who created the bases, airfields and roads, to the federal Highway Trust program, which created thousands of jobs for operating engineers.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] IUOE locals and the IUOE national organization run training facilities throughout the country.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] The largest training facility, the International Training & Education Center (ITEC), is located in Crosby, Texas, and covers 265 acres.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] The purpose of the ITEC is to provide hands-on training and education for union members in North America on new technologies and methodologies in construction such as excavation, drones, earthmoving, crane operation, mechanics, welding, and OSHA guidelines.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] Technology and equipment providers such as Tadano, Link-Belt Cranes, Terex Cranes, Manitowoc Cranes, Liebherr, Morrow Equipment, and Built Robotics donate, fund, or partner with the Union in providing access to different types of technology.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] These include cranes, virtual simulators, drones, autonomous equipment, welding bays, and heavy equipment.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] Additional industry partners include Lincoln Electric, Genie, DeWalt, Proto, Mac Tools, Lenox, John Deere, Caterpillar, Komatsu, and Simformotion.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/international-union-of-operating-engineers] On April 10, 2019, President Donald Trump visited the IUOE Training and Education Center and issued two executive orders to change the process for how pipeline projects were approved, which aimed to simplify the process for oil and gas companies in the United States.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-center-for-construction-education-and-research] The **National Center for Construction Education and Research** (**NCCER**) is an American not-for-profit 501(c)(3) education foundation for professional craft certification, formed in 1996.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-center-for-construction-education-and-research] The mission of NCCER is to provide rigorous and relevant workforce development solutions that create opportunities for individual career advancement and support industry growth.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-center-for-construction-education-and-research] NCCER is recognized across the United States for its breadth of trade curricula, which span over 40 trades, and its workforce development system, which includes accreditation, training, assessment, certification and career development solutions for the construction and maintenance industries.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-center-for-construction-education-and-research] After becoming NCCER-accredited, organizations can provide programs that lead to industry-recognized credentials for their learners.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-center-for-construction-education-and-research] The assessment for certification has two parts: the journey-level knowledge assessment and the performance evaluation.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-center-for-construction-education-and-research] Passing both the written assessment and the performance verification for a craft results in an NCCER Certification.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-center-for-construction-education-and-research] In 1991, eleven prolific construction companies met to address skilled worker shortages and create standard curricula with industry-recognized credentials.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-center-for-construction-education-and-research] In 1993, the organization released the Master Trainer Instructor Certification Program, the Instructor Certification Training Program, and accreditation guidelines.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-center-for-construction-education-and-research] That same year, fifty-three organizations applied for accreditation and the first completed module was entered into a "Registry System." On January 1, 1996, the foundation became recognized as a 501(c)(3) non-profit.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-center-for-construction-education-and-research] OSHA formally recognized NCCER Crane Operator Certification Program on May 20, 2010.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-center-for-construction-education-and-research] The National Training Service Agreement (NTSA) currently has more than 140 contractors and association contributors and contractors can be directly reimbursed for approved training and workforce development expenditures.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-center-for-construction-education-and-research] Participants also support development and industry advancement of craft training provided by NCCER.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-commission-for-certifying-agencies] The **Institute for Credentialing Excellence** (**I.C.E.**) is one of the two main U.S. organizations that accredit personnel certifications or certificates.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-commission-for-certifying-agencies] In November 2009 the ICE formally changed its name from the National Organization for Competency Assurance (NOCA).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-commission-for-certifying-agencies] I.C.E. is an accredited standards developer by the American National Standards Institute.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-commission-for-certifying-agencies] In cooperation with the federal government, the National Commission for Health Certifying Agencies (NCHCA) was founded in 1977 in order to develop standards for voluntary certification programs.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-commission-for-certifying-agencies] In 1989, the NCHCA was expanded to developing certifications for all professions, becoming the National Commission for Certifying Agencies (NCCA), and forming the National Organization for Competency Assurance (NOCA) as a membership association for credentialing bodies.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-commission-for-certifying-agencies] In 2009, the Board moved to change to a new name and became the Institute for Credentialing Excellence (ICE).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-commission-for-certifying-agencies] The National Commission for Certifying Agencies (NCCA) is the accreditation body of the Institute for Credentialing Excellence.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-commission-for-certifying-agencies] The NCCA's Standards for the *Accreditation of Certification Programs* exceed the requirements set forth by the American Psychological Association and the US Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-commission-for-certifying-agencies] In the state of California all organizations that wish to be recognized as counselor certifying organizations must be accredited by the NCCA.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-commission-for-certifying-agencies] The Institute for Credentialing Excellence has no employees.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-commission-for-certifying-agencies] Instead, it pays Smitbucklin Corporation, a for-profit corporation, to employ individuals who run the Institute for Credentialing Excellence.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/national-commission-for-certifying-agencies] Smithbucklin Corporation received $2 million out of the $3.5 million of revenue received by the Institute for Credentialing Excellence in 2018.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Negotiated rulemaking, sometimes abbreviated as "neg reg" or "reg neg", emerged most prominently in the early 1980s because of a concern that traditional rulemaking procedures had become too adversarial.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] John Dunlop, Secretary of Labor under President Gerald Ford, first introduced the idea of formally engaging affected interests in negotiations over federal regulations in the 1970s.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Environmental Protection Agency and the United States Department of Transportation were the first agencies to experiment with negotiated rulemaking.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Other agencies were more reluctant to try it, out of concern about its legality.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] A believer in the effectiveness of neg reg, President Clinton encouraged agencies to use the approach in Executive Order #12866 and in a subsequent Presidential Memorandum.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Although only a small fraction of all regulations have been developed through negotiated rulemaking, a variety of federal government agencies have used the procedure, including the U.S.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Departments of Education, Housing and Urban Development, Health and Human Services, the Interior, Labor, and Transportation, and the U.S.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Negotiated rulemaking is currently required under the Higher Education Act and the Native American Housing Assistance and Self-Determination Act.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Usually, an agency is not mandated to use negotiated rulemaking, but does so by choice.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Its decision to use negotiated rulemaking is not subject to review by the courts.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] An agency can publish a proposal adopted by its negotiating committee, but the Negotiated Rulemaking Act does not require it.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] The decision to use negotiated rulemaking is based on a number of factors, including whether it is likely that a balanced committee can be formed and whether it is reasonable to believe that the committee will reach a consensus recommendation for a proposed rule.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] The agency's resources are also considered.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] The use of a convener to determine the feasibility of undertaking a negotiated rulemaking is authorized under the Negotiated Rulemaking Act.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] A convener may also recommend a list of stakeholder representatives for participation on the neg reg advisory committee.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Sometimes, the agency compiles its own list.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Regardless, the proposed advisory committee members and the issues to be negotiated are published in the Federal Register and subject to public comment.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] People who feel they are under-represented on the committee can request membership.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Neg Regs are facilitated by a public policy mediator.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Once established under the Federal Advisory Committee Act, the committee prepares a set of ground rules, which include the committee's deadline, mission, responsibilities, commitments, and a decision rule or definition of consensus.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] A final list of the issues to be negotiated is also created, and negotiators are provided with relevant background materials.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] With the public policy mediator providing focus and managing the negotiations, the committee discusses each issue striving for agreements in concept, which government staff draft as regulatory text.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] This draft text is reviewed and revised until a tentative consensus agreement is reached.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] If an early consensus cannot be reached, the drafting team outlines multiple options discussed.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] When tentative agreements are reached on all issues, the agreements are checked for consistency before final consensus is achieved.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Negotiated rulemaking typically takes six months to a year and involves multi-day meetings approximately once a month.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] In a study published in 1997, University of Pennsylvania Law School Professor Cary Coglianese reported that negotiated rulemaking did not provide the benefits advocates of the procedure had promised, namely decreased litigation and more expeditious rulemaking.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] At the agency that had conducted the most rules developed with neg reg at the time of his research - the EPA - 50% of the negotiated rules resulted in litigation, compared with an overall rate closer to 25%.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Coglianese also found that negotiated rulemaking did not save agencies any time.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] In a subsequent paper, public policy mediator Susan Podziba has argued that negotiated rulemaking allows the benefits of face-to-face interaction and cooperation.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] She has also claimed that it allows all parties to share information and take advantage of the different skill sets of committee members.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Laura Langbein of the School of Public Affairs at American University indicated that rules developed through neg reg were perceived by survey respondents to be of better quality, more accurate and timelier than rules created using the traditional process.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Another criticism of negotiated rulemaking is that it subverts the public interest because special interest groups have too much sway.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Professor Jody Freeman of Harvard Law School argues against this idea and asserts that the phrase "public interest" is far too vague to act as a variable in the assessment of negotiated rulemaking.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/negotiated-rulemaking] Environmental Protection Agency Public co-sponsored a workshop to reflect on lessons learned during past negotiated rulemakings conducted throughout the federal government.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofit organizations are subject to a non-distribution constraint, meaning that any revenue exceeding expenses must be used to further the organization’s purpose.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Depending on local laws, nonprofits may include charities, political organizations, schools, hospitals, business associations, churches, foundations, social clubs, and cooperatives.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] In some countries nonprofit entities can obtain tax-exempt status and may also qualify to receive tax-deductible contributions; however, an organization can still be a nonprofit without having tax exemption.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Key aspects of nonprofit organizations are their ability to fulfill their mission with respect to accountability, integrity, trustworthiness, honesty, and openness to every person who has invested time, money, and faith into the organization.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofit organizations are accountable to the donors, founders, volunteers, program recipients, and the public community.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Theoretically, for a nonprofit that seeks to finance its operations through donations, public confidence is a factor in the amount of money that a nonprofit organization is able to raise.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Presumably, the more a nonprofit focuses on their mission, the more public confidence they will gain.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] This may result in more money for the organization.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofit organizations are not driven by generating profit, but they must bring in enough income to pursue their social goals.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofits are able to raise money in different ways.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] This includes income from donations from individual donors or foundations, sponsorship from corporations, government funding, programs, services, merchandise sales, and investments.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] With an increase in NPOs since 2010, some organizations have adopted competitive advantages to create revenue for themselves to remain financially stable.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Donations from private individuals or organizations can change each year and government grants have diminished.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] With changes in funding from year to year, many nonprofit organizations have been moving toward increasing the diversity of their funding sources.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] For example, many nonprofits that have relied on government grants have started fundraising efforts to appeal to individual donors.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Most nonprofits have staff that work for the organization, possibly using volunteers to perform the nonprofit's services under the direction of the paid staff.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofits must be careful to balance the salaries paid to staff against the money paid to provide services to the nonprofit's beneficiaries.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Organizations whose salary expenses are too high relative to their program expenses may face regulatory scrutiny.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Some have the misconception that nonprofit organizations may not make a profit.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Although the goal of nonprofits is not specifically to maximize profits, they still have to operate as a fiscally responsible business.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] They must manage their income (grants, donations, and income from services) and expenses so as to remain a fiscally viable entity.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofits have the responsibility of focusing on being professional and financially responsible, replacing self-interest and profit motive with mission motive.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Though nonprofits are managed differently from for-profit businesses, they have felt pressure to be more businesslike.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] To combat private and public business growth in the public service industry, some nonprofits have modeled their business management and mission, shifting their reason of existing to establish sustainability and growth.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Setting effective missions is a key for the successful management of nonprofit organizations.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] There are three important conditions for effective mission: opportunity, competence, and commitment.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] One way of managing the sustainability of nonprofit organizations is to establish strong relations with donor groups.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] This requires a donor marketing strategy, something many nonprofits lack.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofit organizations need to motivate staff, maintain and communicate a vision, set a strategic direction, manage change effectively, and provide a safe working environment for employees, volunteers, and visitors.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] These issues are comparable to those affecting a commercial business but factors which place a nonprofit organization at risk have been identified such as lack of direction or clear purpose, over-centralized management and decision-making, and lack of engagement with staff.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Some nonprofit organizations provide public goods that are undersupplied by government.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] NPOs have a wide diversity of structures and purposes.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Some of the above must be (in most jurisdictions in the US at least) expressed in the organization's charter of establishment or constitution.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Others may be provided by the supervising authority at each particular jurisdiction.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] While affiliations will not affect a legal status, they may be taken into consideration by legal proceedings as an indication of purpose.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Most countries have laws that regulate the establishment and management of NPOs and that require compliance with corporate governance regimes.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Most larger organizations are required to publish their financial reports detailing their income and expenditure publicly.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] In many aspects, they are similar to corporate business entities though there are often significant differences.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Both non-profit and for-profit corporate entities must have board members or trustees who owe the organization a fiduciary duty of loyalty and trust.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] A notable exception to this involves churches, which are often not required to disclose finances to anyone, including church members.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] In the United States, nonprofit organizations are formed by filing bylaws, articles of incorporation, or both in the state in which they expect to operate.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] The act of incorporation creates a legal entity enabling the organization to be treated as a distinct body (corporation) by law and to enter into business dealings, form contracts, and own property as individuals or for-profit corporations can.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] There is an important distinction in the US between *non-profit* and *not-for-profit organizations* (NFPOs); while an NFPO does not profit its owners, and money goes into running the organization, it is not required to operate for the public good.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] An example is a sports club, whose purpose is its members' enjoyment.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] The names used and precise regulations vary from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofits can have members, but many do not.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] The nonprofit may also be a trust or association of members.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] The organization may be controlled by its members who elect the board of directors, board of governors, or board of trustees.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] A nonprofit may have a delegate structure to allow for the representation of groups or corporations as members.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Alternatively, it may be a non-membership organization and the board of directors may elect its own successors.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] The two major types of nonprofit organizations are membership and board-only.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] A membership organization elects the board and has regular meetings and the power to amend the bylaws.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] A board-only organization typically has a self-selected board and a membership whose powers are limited to those delegated to it by the board.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] A board-only organization's bylaws may even state that the organization does not have any membership, although the organization's literature may refer to its donors or service recipients as 'members'.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Examples of such organizations are FairVote and the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] The Model Nonprofit Corporation Act imposes many complexities and requirements on membership decision-making.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Accordingly, many organizations, such as the Wikimedia Foundation, have formed board-only structures.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] The National Association of Parliamentarians has generated concerns about the implications of this trend for the future of openness, accountability, and understanding of public concerns in nonprofit organizations.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] A rebuttal to this might be that as nonprofit organizations grow and seek larger donations, the degree of scrutiny increases, including expectations of audited financial statements.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] A further rebuttal might be that NPOs are constrained, by their choice of legal structure, from financial benefit as far as distribution of profit to members and directors is concerned.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] According to the National Center for Charitable Statistics (NCCS), there are more than 1.5 million nonprofit organizations registered in the United States, including public charities, private foundations, and other nonprofit organizations.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] According to the Giving USA 2025 report, which details philanthropic data from 2024, charitable giving in the United States reached an estimated $557.08 billion.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] In addition to financial support, volunteering remains a cornerstone of the sector.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] A 2025 report from AmeriCorps found that 56.7 million adults formally volunteered with an organization, contributing an estimated $145 billion in economic value to their communities.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] In the United States, both nonprofit organizations and *not-for-profit organizations* may be tax-exempt.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] There are various types of nonprofit exemptions, such as 501(c)(3) organizations that are a religious, charitable, or educational-based organization that does not influence state and federal legislation, and 501(c)(7) organizations that are for pleasure, recreation, or another nonprofit purpose.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] There is an important distinction in the US between *non-profit* and *not-for-profit organizations* (NFPOs).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] While an NFPO does not profit its owners, and money goes into running the organization, it is not required to operate for the public good.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] An example is a club whose purpose is its members' enjoyment.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Other examples of NFPOs include credit unions, sports clubs, and advocacy groups.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Nonprofit organizations provide services to the community such as aid and development programs, medical research, education, and health services.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Some nonprofits are both member-serving and community-serving.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Examples of these are homeowners associations, the American Red Cross, and Habitat for Humanity.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] In 2020, some nonprofit organizations began using microblogging (brief videos with short text formats) on TikTok to reach Gen Z, engage with community stakeholders, and overall build community.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] TikTok allowed for innovative engagement between nonprofit organizations and younger generations.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Some organizations offer new, positive-sounding alternative terminology to describe the sector.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] The term *civil society organization* (CSO) has been used by a growing number of organizations, including the *Center for the Study of Global Governance*.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] The term *citizen sector organization* (CSO) has also been advocated to describe the sector – as one of citizens, for citizens – by organizations including Ashoka: Innovators for the Public.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Advocates argue that these terms describe the sector in its own terms, without relying on terminology used for the government or business sectors.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] However, use of terminology by a nonprofit of self-descriptive language that is not legally compliant risks confusing the public about nonprofit abilities, capabilities, and limitations.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] In some countries nonprofits may apply for tax-exempt status.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Tax exemptions have been justified by community benefit of some organizations.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Studies argue that the community benefits of non-profits have be overestimated and can be negative compared to for-profit organizations when including the cost of the tax exemptions and costs due to financial mismanagement.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] The discretionary process of tax exemptions application can result in corruption or fraud.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] In the United States, to be exempt from federal income taxes, the organization must meet the requirements set forth in the Internal Revenue Code (IRC).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Granting nonprofit status is done by the state, while granting tax-exempt designation (such as IRC 501(c)) is granted by the federal government via the IRS.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] This means that not all nonprofits are eligible to be tax-exempt.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] For example, employees of non-profit organizations pay taxes from their salaries, which they receive according to the laws of the country.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] NPOs use the model of a double bottom line in that furthering their cause is more important than making a profit, though both are needed to ensure the organization's sustainability.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] An advantage of nonprofits registered in the UK is that they benefit from some reliefs and exemptions.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Charities and nonprofits are exempt from Corporation Tax as well as the trustees being exempt from Income Tax.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] There may also be tax relief available for charitable giving, via Gift Aid, monetary donations, and legacies.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Financial mismanagement is a particular problem with NPOs because the employees are not accountable to anyone who has a direct stake in the organization.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] For example, an employee may start a new program without disclosing its complete liabilities.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] The employee may be rewarded for improving the NPO's reputation, making other employees happy, and attracting new donors.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Liabilities promised on the full faith and credit of the organization but not recorded anywhere constitute accounting fraud.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] But even indirect liabilities negatively affect the financial sustainability of the NPO, and the NPO will have financial problems unless strict controls are instated.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Some commenters have argued that the receipt of significant funding from large for-profit corporations can ultimately alter the NPO's functions.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] A frequent measure of an NPO's efficiency is its expense ratio (i.e. expenditures on things other than its programs, divided by its total expenditures).
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Tax exempt status of NPOs can, under circumstances such as mismanagement, create negative value for society.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Reduced transparency requirements or limitations on freedom of information laws can in some cases result in financial crimes, see also non-profit organizations and access to public information.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Low wages have resulted in some cases in exploitation of labour.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] While many established NPOs are well-funded and comparative to their competitors, many more are independent and must be creative with which incentives they use to attract and maintain people.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] The initial interest for many is the remuneration package, though many who have been questioned after leaving an NPO have reported that it was stressful work environments and the workload.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Public- and private-sector employment have, for the most part, been able to offer more to their employees than most nonprofit agencies throughout history.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Either in the form of higher wages, more comprehensive benefit packages, or less tedious work, the public and private sectors have enjoyed an advantage over NPOs in attracting employees.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Traditionally, the NPO has attracted mission-driven individuals who want to assist their chosen cause.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Compounding the issue is that some NPOs do not operate in a manner similar to most businesses, or they operate only on a seasonal basis.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] This leads many young and driven employees to forego NPOs in favor of more stable employment.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Today, however, nonprofit organizations are adopting methods used by their competitors and finding new means to retain their employees and attract the best of the newly minted workforce.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Some believe that most nonprofits will never be able to match the pay of the private sector. and therefore should focus their attention on implementing pleasurable work environments.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] For some, a good environment is more important than salary.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Other incentives that could be implemented are flexible work hours.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Founder's syndrome is an issue some organizations experience as they expand.
[src:accredited-crane-operator-certification/nonprofit-organization] Dynamic founders, who have a strong vision of how to operate the project, try to retain control of the organization, even as new employees or volunteers want to expand the project's scope or change policy.
